# Fusion-Space Reconstruction for Missing-Modality Sentiment Analysis


## Abstract

When the text modality goes missing at inference time, multimodal sentiment analysis degrades sharply. Existing generative methods try to recover missing inputs by reconstructing raw features—a high-dimensional space that demands heavy decoder networks and, in practice, hundreds of thousands of parameters per modality. We explore an alternative: instead of raw features, reconstruct the missing modality's representation directly in the model's own compact, 40-dimensional fusion space, where all modalities are already projected and aligned. Across 106 experiments on MOSEI and MOSI, fusion-space reconstruction outperforms raw-feature-space alternatives while using 23× fewer parameters (+0.012 MissT on MOSEI). A deterministic 12K-parameter MLP reconstructor (DetMLP) matches a 30K conditional VAE on predictive accuracy (MissT 0.588 vs. 0.586), raising the question of whether the VAE machinery is necessary for this task. Removing the reconstruction auxiliary task costs 0.034 MissT and inflates cross-seed variance fivefold, while removing only the KL term leaves accuracy intact—the reconstruction objective itself, rather than KL regularization, drives the gain. Among the hyperparameters studied, KL weight dominates, accounting for 63.3% of MissT variance, with an optimal range (β = 0.4–0.8) far from the conventional VAE default of β = 0.1. Auxiliary strategies such as MC inference and contrastive alignment help at low KL but contribute nothing at the optimal regime, and contrastive alignment introduces marked seed instability. Under identical encoder backbones and classical features, our 12K-parameter DetMLP outperforms three published missing-modality methods—alignment-based MissModal (TACL 2023), gradient-based GMD (AAAI 2024), and denoising-complementation TMDC (AAAI 2026)—while using fewer reconstruction parameters.

---

## 1. Introduction

Multimodal sentiment analysis (MSA) jointly models text, audio, and visual signals to understand human emotion, with applications spanning conversational AI to mental health monitoring. Transformer-based fusion architectures (Tsai et al., 2019; Guo et al., 2025) deliver strong results when all modalities are available. In real-world deployments, however, modalities routinely go missing—a user turns off their camera, speaks in a noisy room, or blocks text access through privacy settings. Missing text is the most common and the most damaging failure mode. On standard MSA benchmarks, text alone accounts for an $R^2$ of 0.268; audio and vision contribute −0.102 individually and −0.078 jointly. When text disappears, the remaining modalities carry essentially no sentiment signal.

Existing work on missing-modality robustness divides into two camps. **Passive methods** treat the missing modality as a perturbation to tolerate. Uncertainty-aware gating (Yang et al., 2024) down-weights unreliable modalities, and evidential fusion (Amini et al., 2020) models predictive uncertainty. These approaches share a fundamental ceiling: they can only redistribute attention across what remains—they cannot recover what is absent. **Generative methods** attempt active recovery by reconstructing the missing modality. P-RMF (Li et al., ACL 2025) trains separate VAEs per modality to regenerate raw features. HVDER (2026) pairs VAE encoding with a diffusion decoder. But raw-feature reconstruction is a hard problem: modality dimensions span two orders of magnitude (text 768d, audio 25d, vision 171d), and the networks needed to bridge this gap are large—typically 10–50× the parameter cost of our approach.

Our proposal is to reconstruct the missing modality's representation in the model's own 40-dimensional fusion space rather than in raw feature space. All three modalities are projected to this shared 40d subspace through identical Transformer encoders before fusion—it is already semantically compressed and cross-modally aligned, making reconstruction a substantially easier learning problem than in raw space. We test two instantiations: **CVAE-MSA**, a conditional VAE with a 30K-parameter reconstructor (MLP encoder → latent → MLP decoder), and **DetMLP**, a deterministic MLP with 12K parameters that directly maps available modalities to the missing modality's fusion embedding. Both use deterministic inference at test time (CVAE sets the latent prior mean $z=0$), avoiding sampling overhead.

The experiments reveal several patterns that run counter to assumptions common in the missing-modality literature.

The reconstruction space matters far more than the choice of generative framework. DetMLP (12K params, 40d output) achieves MissT 0.588±0.015 on MOSEI, matching the 30K CVAE (0.586±0.006). A raw-feature-space MLP with 282K parameters and a 768d output underperforms by 0.012 MissT. In this setting, the VAE-vs-MLP decision is largely irrelevant compared to the fusion-space-vs-raw-space decision.

KL regularization dominates all other hyperparameters, accounting for 63.3% of MissT variance (Figure 3). Its optimal range, β = 0.4–0.8, sits far from the conventional VAE default of β = 0.1. Yet KL is not needed for predictive accuracy—DetMLP without any KL term reaches the same MissT as CVAE, albeit with 2.5× larger cross-seed variance (±0.015 vs. ±0.006). KL appears to function primarily as a training stabilizer.

The reconstruction auxiliary task is essential. Training CVAE without it (KL only) drops MissT by 0.034 and blows up cross-seed variance to ±0.033. The reconstruction objective, rather than the KL regularizer, is the active ingredient.

The benefits of auxiliary strategies—MC inference and contrastive alignment—decay to zero as KL weight increases. They provide substantial gains at low KL (+4–6pp at β = 0.1) but become redundant under adequate KL regularization. Contrastive alignment also introduces marked seed instability (σ = 0.013 across two validated seeds), which limits its practical value.

We contribute fusion-space reconstruction as a lightweight method—adding as few as 12K parameters (3.4% overhead) to the encoder backbone—and show that it outperforms three published missing-modality methods (MissModal, GMD, TMDC) under controlled comparison on MOSEI with classical features. On the analysis side, we provide what is, to our knowledge, the first systematic hyperparameter study for reconstruction-based missing-modality methods, establishing KL weight as the dominant factor (63% of variance), documenting the decay of auxiliary strategy benefits with KL, and identifying contrastive alignment's seed instability. Controlled ablation experiments confirm that fusion space beats raw feature space, a 12K MLP matches a 30K VAE, and the reconstruction objective is indispensable. MOSEI subsample experiments further reveal non-trivial interactions between dataset size and reconstruction effectiveness—the relationship is not simply "more data helps."

---

## 2. Related Work

### 2.1 Multimodal Sentiment Analysis

Multimodal sentiment analysis has progressed from early fusion methods to Transformer-based architectures. Tensor Fusion Network (Zadeh et al., EMNLP 2017) and Low-rank Multimodal Fusion (Liu et al., ACL 2018) modeled pairwise and tensor-product interactions but struggled with unaligned sequences. MulT (Tsai et al., ACL 2019) introduced directional pairwise cross-modal attention for asynchronous modalities. CASP (Guo et al., AAAI 2025) proposed three-stage training—pretrain, contrastive, pseudo-label—with modality-specific Transformer encoders and late fusion, achieving strong results with classical features. All methods in our study share CASP's encoder backbone (identical Conv1d projections and 5-layer Transformers), isolating the effect of the fusion strategy.

Beyond classical features, SDUMC (Cong et al., ICASSP 2025) uses WavLM and BERT for stronger representations, and LLM-based methods (MSE-Adapter, AAAI 2025; DashFusion, 2025) fine-tune large language models with parameter-efficient adapters. These feature-level advances are orthogonal to our contribution: our methods operate at the fusion architecture level and can combine with any feature extraction backbone.

### 2.2 Missing Modality Robustness

**Passive tolerance** methods treat missing modalities as input corruption to be absorbed. Zero-filling remains a surprisingly strong baseline (Parthasarathy and Sundaram, 2021; Guo et al., 2025). MissModal (Lin and Hu, TACL 2023) applies contrastive and distributional alignment losses to pull missing-modal representations toward their complete-modal counterparts. GMD (Wang et al., AAAI 2024) detects gradient conflicts across modality combinations and uses Dynamic Sharing to skip missing encoders. TMDC (AAAI 2026) employs two-stage denoising—modality-specific and modality-common denoisers, followed by a complementation module. MissModal and GMD share a hard ceiling: they regularize representations or training dynamics but cannot synthesize information that is absent. TMDC's complementation module takes a partial step beyond this, predicting cross-modal common features, but it operates on shared rather than modality-specific representations.

**Generative** methods reconstruct the missing modality outright. P-RMF (Li et al., ACL 2025) trains three separate VAEs, one per modality, for raw-feature reconstruction. HVDER (2026) pairs a VAE encoder with a diffusion decoder. Both operate in raw feature space—768 dimensions for text alone—where dimensions are high and heterogeneous, forcing large networks (500K–1.5M reconstructor parameters). Our methods reconstruct in a 40d fusion space where modalities are already aligned and compressed, keeping reconstructors lightweight (12–30K parameters).

Table A provides a systematic comparison of our approach with existing missing-modality methods.

| Method | Reconstruction Space | Architecture | Reconstructor Params | Per-Modality? |
|--------|---------------------|--------------|:--:|:--:|
| Zero-filling (CASP) | — (passive) | — | 0 | — |
| MissModal (Lin et al., TACL 2023) | — (alignment loss) | Contrast+Dist+Sent loss | 13K (proj head) | No |
| GMD (Wang et al., AAAI 2024) | — (gradient-based) | Multi-combo training + DS | 0 | No |
| TMDC (AAAI 2026) | Shared (40d) | Denoising + Complementation | 19K | No |
| MMIN (Zhao et al., 2020) | Raw feature (768d) | Cascaded residual AE | ~500K | Yes |
| P-RMF (Li et al., ACL 2025) | Raw feature (768d) | 3× VAE | ~1.5M | Yes |
| **DetMLP (Ours)** | **Fusion (40d)** | **MLP** | **12K** | **No** |
| **CVAE-MSA (Ours)** | **Fusion (40d)** | **Conditional VAE** | **30K** | **No** |

*Table A: Comparison with existing missing-modality methods. Our fusion-space methods use the fewest reconstruction parameters. The top four rows (MissModal, GMD, TMDC, plus zero-filling) were re-implemented under our controlled encoder-and-feature setting for direct comparison (Table 1).*

### 2.3 Conditional VAEs and Posterior Collapse

The VAE (Kingma and Welling, ICLR 2014) provides a principled framework for latent-variable generative modeling. The CVAE (Sohn et al., NeurIPS 2015) conditions both encoder and decoder on auxiliary variables. Beta-VAE (Higgins et al., ICLR 2017) weights the KL term to control the information bottleneck—higher β yields more disentangled representations at the cost of reconstruction fidelity. Posterior collapse (Bowman et al., CoNLL 2016), where the decoder ignores the latent variable, is a known failure mode at low KL weight. Mitigation strategies—KL annealing (Bowman et al., 2016), cyclical schedules (Fu et al., NAACL 2019), free bits (Kingma et al., 2016)—were developed primarily for text and image generation. Their role in multimodal fusion and missing-modality reconstruction has received little attention.

**Positioning.** Our work sits at the intersection of these three lines of research. We propose fusion-space reconstruction as a lightweight alternative to raw-space generative recovery, and we conduct a systematic hyperparameter study for reconstruction-based missing-modality methods—an analysis that, to our knowledge, has not been done before. The central empirical result—that fusion-space reconstruction outperforms raw-space alternatives by a wide margin, and that a 12K MLP matches a 30K VAE—suggests that generative models may not be necessary for missing modality recovery when the reconstruction target is chosen carefully. The hyperparameter analysis further shows that KL weight dominates all other factors (63% of variance) and that its effective range (β = 0.4–0.8) differs substantially from the conventional default of β = 0.1.

---

## 3. Method

### 3.1 Problem Formulation

Let $x = \\{x_T, x_A, x_V\\}$ denote the three modalities: text, audio, and vision. Each modality $x_m \\in \\mathbb{R}^{L \\times d_m^{\\text{raw}}}$ is a sequence of $L$ time-aligned feature vectors, where $d_T^{\\text{raw}}=768$ (GloVe), $d_A^{\\text{raw}}=25$ (COVAREP), and $d_V^{\\text{raw}}=171$ (FACET). Each sample has a sentiment label $y \\in \\mathbb{R}$ (regression) with derived binary classification (positive/negative) as the primary evaluation metric.

The standard MSA pipeline consists of three stages:

**Stage 1 — Modality Encoding.** Each modality is independently projected to a common dimensionality and encoded through a modality-specific Transformer:

$$h_m = \\text{Enc}_m(x_m) = \\text{Transformer}_m(\\text{Conv1d}(x_m; d_m^{\\text{raw}} \\to 40)) \\in \\mathbb{R}^{40}, \\quad m \\in \\{T, A, V\\}$$

The three encoders are identical in architecture (5 layers, 8 attention heads, 40-dim embeddings) but have separate parameters. This symmetric design ensures that all modalities are projected to a shared representational space.

**Stage 2 — Fusion.** The modality embeddings are concatenated:

$$h_{\\text{fusion}} = [h_T; h_A; h_V] \\in \\mathbb{R}^{120}$$

**Stage 3 — Prediction.** A lightweight output head maps the fused representation to a sentiment score:

$$\\hat{y} = \\text{Head}(h_{\\text{fusion}}) = W_3 \\cdot \\sigma(W_2 \\cdot \\text{Dropout}(\\sigma(W_1 \\cdot h_{\\text{fusion}} + b_1)) + b_2) + b_3$$
where $W_1 \\in \\mathbb{R}^{80 \\times 120}$, $W_2 \\in \\mathbb{R}^{40 \\times 80}$, $W_3 \\in \\mathbb{R}^{1 \\times 40}$, and $\\sigma$ denotes ReLU activation.

**Missing modality scenario.** When modality $m$ is missing at test time ($x_m = \\emptyset$), the standard baseline sets $h_m = \\mathbf{0}$. Our method generates a reconstruction $\\hat{h}_m$ using the available modalities.

### 3.2 Why Reconstruction in Fusion Space?

Reconstructing in the 40-dimensional fusion space rather than raw feature space is the central design decision behind the method's efficiency. Three properties motivate it:

**Dimensionality reduction.** Fusion space (40d) is 19× smaller than raw text space (768d). The reconstruction target is a compact vector, not a high-dimensional sequence—the decoder only needs to produce 40 values.

**Semantic compression.** The Transformer encoders, trained with a supervised objective, already extract task-relevant features. The fusion embedding $h_m$ discards low-level acoustic and visual artifacts and retains sentiment-relevant semantic content.

**Cross-modal alignment.** All modalities project to the same 40d space and are aligned through the shared prediction objective. The reconstructor's input (available modalities' embeddings) and output (missing modality's embedding) live in compatible representational spaces.

Prior work (P-RMF, HVDER) operates in raw feature space, where input (audio 25d + vision 171d = 196d) and output (text 768d) are both high-dimensional and heterogeneous. The reconstruction network must implicitly bridge modalities with vastly different dimensionalities and statistical properties—hence the need for substantially larger architectures.

### 3.3 Reconstruction Methods

Two instantiations of fusion-space reconstruction are tested, differing in whether they include a probabilistic latent variable.

**CVAE Reconstructor.** A lightweight Conditional VAE reconstructs $h_m^{\\text{missing}}$ from the available modalities' fusion embeddings. It has three components:

**Encoder (Posterior, training only).** The ground-truth $h_m^{\\text{true}}$ is available during training via teacher forcing. The encoder maps the concatenation of available context and the target embedding to a latent Gaussian:

$$q_\\phi(z | h_{\\text{avail}}, h_m^{\\text{true}}) = \\mathcal{N}(\\mu_\\phi, \\sigma_\\phi^2 I)$$

$$[\\mu_\\phi, \\log\\sigma_\\phi^2] = \\text{MLP}_{\\text{enc}}([h_{\\text{avail}}; h_m^{\\text{true}}])$$

where $h_{\\text{avail}} \\in \\mathbb{R}^{80}$ concatenates two available modalities' 40d embeddings. The encoder MLP is $120 \\to 64 \\to 64$ with ReLU, followed by separate linear heads for $\\mu$ (32d) and $\\log\\sigma^2$ (32d).

**Decoder (Likelihood).** The decoder reconstructs the missing representation from a latent sample $z$ and the available context:

$$p_\\theta(h_m | z, h_{\\text{avail}}) = \\text{MLP}_{\\text{dec}}([z; h_{\\text{avail}}])$$

The decoder MLP is $72 \\to 64 \\to 64 \\to 40$ with ReLU. At test time the ground-truth $h_m^{\\text{true}}$ is unavailable, so the prior mean $z = \\mathbf{0}$ is used (deterministic inference). MC sampling ($z \\sim \\mathcal{N}(0,I)$, averaging $K$ samples) provides modest gains at low KL but becomes redundant at the optimal KL regime (Section 5.3).

**Deterministic MLP Reconstructor (DetMLP).** To test whether the VAE framework is necessary, a simpler alternative is implemented: a three-layer MLP that directly maps $h_{\\text{avail}}$ to $h_m^{\\text{recon}}$ with no encoder, latent variables, or KL term:

$$\\hat{h}_m = \\text{MLP}_{\\text{det}}(h_{\\text{avail}}) = W_3 \\cdot \\sigma(W_2 \\cdot \\sigma(W_1 \\cdot h_{\\text{avail}} + b_1) + b_2) + b_3$$
where $W_1 \\in \\mathbb{R}^{64 \\times 80}$, $W_2 \\in \\mathbb{R}^{64 \\times 64}$, $W_3 \\in \\mathbb{R}^{40 \\times 64}$, and $\\sigma$ is ReLU.

DetMLP has 12K parameters—2.5× fewer than the CVAE reconstructor (30K). It is trained with the same regression and MSE reconstruction losses as CVAE, minus the KL term. Both CVAE and DetMLP share the identical encoder backbone and output head; only the reconstructor module differs, giving a controlled ablation of the VAE framework.

Both reconstructors operate on the same fusion-space representations: they receive the same input ($h_{\\text{avail}}$, an 80d concatenation of available modalities) and produce the same output ($\\hat{h}_m$, 40d). They are trained end-to-end with the modality encoders; all 360–378K parameters are jointly optimized.

### 3.4 Training Objective

**CVAE Loss.** The CVAE training loss combines four terms:

$$
\\begin{aligned}
\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{CVAE}} = &\\; \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{reg}}(y, \\hat{y}_{\\text{full}}) \\\\
+ &\\; \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{reg}}(y, \\hat{y}_{\\text{drop}}) \\\\
+ &\\; \\beta \\cdot D_{KL}\\big(q_\\phi(z|h_{\\text{avail}}, h_m^{\\text{true}}) \\;\\parallel\\; \\mathcal{N}(0,I)\\big) \\\\
+ &\\; \\lambda \\cdot \\|\\hat{h}_m - h_m^{\\text{true}}\\|_2^2
\\end{aligned}
$$

where $\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{reg}}$ is L1 loss on the full-modality prediction (first term) and the modality-dropped prediction (second term), $\\beta$ is the KL weight, and $\\lambda$ is the reconstruction weight.

**DetMLP Loss.** DetMLP drops the KL term:

$$
\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{DetMLP}} = \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{reg}}(y, \\hat{y}_{\\text{full}}) + \\mathcal{L}_{\\text{reg}}(y, \\hat{y}_{\\text{drop}}) + \\lambda \\cdot \\|\\hat{h}_m - h_m^{\\text{true}}\\|_2^2
$$
$\\lambda$ is fixed at 1.0 based on the hyperparameter sweep.

**Training procedure.** One modality is uniformly sampled for dropping per batch ($\\frac{1}{3}$ probability each). Its true embedding $h_m^{\\text{true}}$ feeds the CVAE encoder via teacher forcing (when applicable), but is replaced by the reconstructed $\\hat{h}_m$ in the fusion layer. Available modalities pass through unchanged. All parameters—encoders, reconstructor, output head—are jointly optimized. The encoders are not frozen; the "12–30K additional parameters" count refers to the reconstructor module only. The full model contains 360–378K parameters depending on variant.

### 3.5 Architecture Summary

| Component | Specification | Parameters |
|-----------|--------------|:---:|
| Text Encoder | Conv1d(768→40) + Transformer(5L, 8H, 40d) | ~120K |
| Audio Encoder | Conv1d(25→40) + Transformer(5L, 8H, 40d) | ~108K |
| Vision Encoder | Conv1d(171→40) + Transformer(5L, 8H, 40d) | ~112K |
| CVAE Encoder (CVAE only) | MLP(120→64→64) → μ(32d), logσ²(32d) | ~13K |
| CVAE Decoder (CVAE only) | MLP(72→64→64→40) | ~13K |
| DetMLP (DetMLP only) | MLP(80→64→64→40) | ~12K |
| Output Head | Linear(120→80→40→1) | ~11K |
| **CVAE Total** | | **~378K** |
| **DetMLP Total** | | **~360K** |

![Figure 6: CVAE-MSA Architecture — full pipeline from modality inputs through encoders, CVAE reconstructor, fusion, and output](figures/fig6_architecture.png)

